04876nam a22008055i 9780674419612DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979621917  a97806744196127 a10.4159/harvard.97806744196122doi  a(DE-B1597)427271  a(OCoLC)882257921  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a333.790973223  aZP 30502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/157938:1 aJones, Christopher F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRoutes of Power :bEnergy and Modern America /cChristopher F. Jones. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b13 halftones, 11 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Coal’s Liquid Pathways -- t2. The Anthracite Energy Transition -- t3. Pennsylvania’s Petroleum Boom -- t4. Pipelines and Power -- t5. Taming the Susquehanna River -- t6 The Electrification of America -- tCONCLUSION -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe fossil fuel revolution is usually rendered as a tale of historic advances in energy production. In this perspective-changing account, Christopher F. Jones instead tells a story of advances in energy access--canals, pipelines, and wires that delivered power in unprecedented quantities to cities and factories at a great distance from production sites. He shows that in the American mid-Atlantic region between 1820 and 1930, the construction of elaborate transportation networks for coal, oil, and electricity unlocked remarkable urban and industrial growth along the eastern seaboard. But this new transportation infrastructure did not simply satisfy existing consumer demand--it also whetted an appetite for more abundant and cheaper energy, setting the nation on a path toward fossil fuel dependence. Between the War of 1812 and the Great Depression, low-cost energy supplied to cities through a burgeoning delivery system allowed factory workers to mass-produce goods on a scale previously unimagined. It also allowed people and products to be whisked up and down the East Coast at speeds unattainable in a country dependent on wood, water, and muscle. But an energy-intensive America did not benefit all its citizens equally. It provided cheap energy to some but not others; it channeled profits to financiers rather than laborers; and it concentrated environmental harms in rural areas rather than cities. Today, those who wish to pioneer a more sustainable and egalitarian energy order can learn valuable lessons from this history of the nation's first steps toward dependence on fossil fuels.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEnergieversorgung. 0aEnergieversorgungsnetz. 0aEnergy consumption. 0aEnergy development. 0aEnergy policy. 0aPower resources. 0aStrukturwandel. 0aTransportation. 0aWirtschaft. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2014z9783110370225oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441961240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674419612423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674419612.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SS